SIMPLE: purify
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Purify
<hw>Pu"ri*fy</hw> <pr>(p⟦umac⟧"r⟦icr⟧*f⟦imac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Purified</conjf>
<pr>(p⟦umac⟧"r⟦icr⟧*f⟦imac⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Purifying</conjf>
<pr>(p⟦umac⟧"r⟦icr⟧*f⟦imac⟧"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>purifier</ets>, L. <ets>purificare</ets>; <ets>purus</ets> pure +
<ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>Pure</er>, and
<er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make pure or clear from
material defilement, admixture, or imperfection; to free from extraneous
or noxious matter; <as>as, to <ex>purify</ex> liquors or metals; to
<ex>purify</ex> the blood; to <ex>purify</ex> the air.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, in figurative uses: <sd>(a)</sd> To free from
guilt or moral defilement; <as>as, to <ex>purify</ex> the
heart</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And fit them so⟦br⟧
<qex>Purified</qex> to receive him pure.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>To free from ceremonial or legal
defilement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Moses took the blood, and put it upon the horns of the altar,
. . . and <qex>purified</qex> the altar.</q> <rj><qau>Lev. viii.
15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Purify</qex> both yourselves and your captives.</q> <rj><qau>
Num. xxxi. 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>To free from improprieties or barbarisms; <as>as,
to <ex>purify</ex> a language</as>.</def> <rj><au>Sprat.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purify</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Purify
<hw>Pu"ri*fy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow or become pure or
clear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purim</ent>⟦br⟧
